{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BrRmMXmDYxs5PwXuRCvmbn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the failure patterns from the digest and write a feedback.md file.\n\nLooking at the failures, I can identify these patterns:\n\n1. **OCR corruption - digit/letter substitution** (1→l/i, 0→O, 5→S, etc.): The extractor returns the corrupted title as-is instead of normalizing it.\n   - Barszcz Czerwony: \"B4RSZCZ CZERWONY\" extracted as-is\n   - Beet Arugula Salad: \"BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD\" extracted as-is\n   - Blackberry Fool: \"B1ACKBERRY FOO1\"\n   - Chleb Pszenny Razowy: \"CH1EB PSZENNY RAZOWY\"\n   - Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi: \"KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi\"\n   - Lemon Herb Grilled Chicken: \"LEMON HERB GRILÍED CHICKEN\"\n   - Makowiec ze Śliwkami: \"MAK0WIEC ZE ŚLIWKAMI + SERVÍNG AND STORAGE:\"\n   - Pierniki Śliwkowe: \"P1ERNIKI ŚLIWK\" (truncated)\n   - Sole with Brown Butter and Capers: \"S01e with Brown Butter and Capers\"\n   - Tomato Lentil Soup: \"TOMATO LENT1L SOUP\"\n   - Bigos Śliwkowy z Bekonem: \"B¡gos Śl¡wkowy z Bekonem\"\n\nThe extractor is finding the correct lines but the OCR corruption remains in the output. I'm realizing this is fundamentally a title extraction task, not a normalization one—the question is whether these should count as successes since the right content was identified, or failures because the extracted text doesn't match the clean expected titles.\n\nLooking more closely at the failures, I'm seeing two distinct patterns. Some cases have the correct title line extracted but with OCR artifacts that would need post-processing to fix. Others are pulling section headers or page numbers entirely—like \"Page 42\" for Baked Cod with Herbs, or \"FISH & SEAFOOD\" for Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce—where the extractor grabbed the wrong structural element altogether.\n\nThere's also content bleeding from previous pages, where the extraction starts with leftover recipe fragments or preamble text instead of the actual title. And when titles have colons marking variations, the extractor is cutting them short, capturing only the first part before the separator. I'm seeing more extraction failures where multi-line titles get split across OCR boundaries—like \"PLACKI / ŻÓŁTE / Z KUKURYDZĄ\" where only the middle portion was captured, or cases where the extractor completely missed the title and grabbed unrelated content like \"TOPPING & BAKING:\" instead. There are also files marked with explicit OCR corruption that return empty results or partial text.\n\nAnother issue is when section headers within the recipe—like \"Na masę:\" or \"Roasting:\"—get mistakenly extracted as the title rather than the actual dish name, suggesting the extractor isn't properly distinguishing between the recipe title and internal structure. I'm seeing a clear pattern now—the extractor is pulling the OCR-corrupted version of recipe titles directly without cleaning them up. So instead of returning \"Barszcz Czerwony,\" it's keeping \"B4RSZCZ,\" and similar character substitutions are appearing across multiple recipes like the arugula salad, the blackberry fool, and the Polish bread recipes.\n\nThere's also a second issue where section headers or page references are being selected as the title instead of the actual recipe name—like when \"Page 42\" gets returned instead of \"Baked Cod with Herbs,\" or the soup extractor grabs \"Page 102 - SOUPS & BROTHS\" rather than the actual dish title.\n\nI'm also seeing cases where leftover content from the previous page appears at the top of the file and gets picked up as the recipe title, and some recipes have compound titles connected by colons or plus signs where only part of the full name is being captured. I'm seeing more cases where multi-line titles get fragmented—like \"PLACKI / ŻÓŁTE / Z KUKURYDZĄ\" where only part gets captured, or \"ROSEMARY / FOCACCIA / BREAD\" where the extractor grabs something unrelated like \"TOPPING & BAKING:\" instead. There's also a pattern emerging with files that have explicit OCR corruption markers in the template, where the extractor either returns nothing or pulls text from within the recipe itself rather than the actual title.\n\nNow I'm noticing another issue: when the title is clearly present at the start of the file, the extractor sometimes skips it entirely and returns a later section header instead—like grabbing \"Na masę:\" from Cheesecake z Jeżynami when the title is right there on line 3, or \"Roasting:\" from Golonka when the title is on line 1.\n\nThere's also a trickier pattern emerging where metadata lines precede the actual title, and the extractor either returns empty or gets confused by the formatting—Ogórkowa Zupa has that metadata line with season and prep time before the title appears, which seems to be throwing things off.\n\nSince all 40 failures are from generated files rather than real ones, that's an important distinction to note when writing up the feedback.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":26259,"cache_read_input_tokens":10352,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":26259},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"53735f72-1291-447c-9abf-b077c22e3b1b","uuid":"4ee46319-bafe-4e67-bc5d-fafd61d21b26"}
